              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 72-year-old retired Czech machinist, a heavyset man with a weathered complexion, nicotine-stained fingers, and a chronic, productive cough that has worsened noticeably over the past several months [MEDDIALOG:C34.9:0]. He presents to the pulmonology clinic complaining of persistent forceful cough producing thick, bubbly secretions, progressive shortness of breath on minimal exertion, a heavy feeling in his chest, and profound fatigue [MEDDIALOG:C34.9:0]. Over the last two weeks he has also noticed intermittent confusion and difficulty finding words, which alarmed his family [MEDDIALOG:C34.9:7].\n\n{patientName} spent over 40 years working in a heavy-machinery factory in Brno, where he was regularly exposed to metal dust and cutting-oil fumes — a recognized occupational inhalation exposure [MEDDIALOG:C34.9:3]. He smoked approximately 30 cigarettes a day for 50 years, only quitting five years ago. He lives with his wife in a modest apartment on the outskirts of the city; their two adult children visit on weekends.\n\nOutside of work, {patientName} used to enjoy fishing along the Svratka river and tending a small vegetable garden, but breathlessness has increasingly curtailed these activities. He has a close circle of retired colleagues he meets weekly at a local hospoda for cards, though he admits he has missed several sessions recently due to fatigue and confusion episodes [MEDDIALOG:C34.9:7]. He is soft-spoken but visibly anxious about his deteriorating condition."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
